# Requirements & Problem Understanding

## Problem Statement

AI agents need **private transactions at machine speed**. Current state:
- x402 enables payments for HTTP resources, but no privacy — every payment is traceable on-chain
- Groth16/Circom proof generation is too slow for high-frequency micro-transactions (5-30s per proof)
- No ZK rollup exists for Stellar — agents either self-custody (slow, bad UX) or use a trusted intermediary
- The agent economy needs sub-second finality and near-zero marginal cost, but on-chain settlement can't provide this

**Reference**: [Psy Protocol](https://psy.xyz/privacy) — client-side ZK proving, recursive aggregation, network verifies only aggregated proofs. Agents execute locally, prove locally, send only ZK proof + state diff to network.

**Who is affected**: AI agents doing high-frequency private transactions. Agent frameworks. Anyone building agent-to-agent payments on Stellar.

**Current workaround**: Centralized intermediaries or no privacy at all.

## Goals & Objectives

**Primary goals**:
1. Agent executes transactions locally (off-chain) and generates ZK proof of correct execution — no server-side prover
2. Recursive ZK aggregation — aggregate many agent proofs into one proof
3. Final aggregated proof settles to Stellar (Soroban contract) — network verifies the aggregate, not individual transactions
4. Private by default — transaction amounts, sender, recipient not visible on-chain
5. Sub-second execution + near-zero marginal cost per transaction

**Non-goals**:
- Multi-chain (Stellar/Soroban only)
- TEE-based approach (pure ZK — no trusted hardware)
- Trusted setup ceremonies (use zkVM with transparent setup or PLONKish)
- Agent identity layer (trust402/identity is a separate concern — this is purely transaction privacy)
- x402 facilitator integration (separate concern — rollup handles settlement, not payment protocol)

## User Stories & Use Cases

**As an agent**, I want to execute a private transaction and have it settle to Stellar in one step, without waiting 5-30s for proof generation or trusting a server-side prover.

**As a user**, I want to pay an agent for a service and have the payment be private — no on-chain link between my payment and the agent's withdrawal.

**As a liquidity provider**, I want to deposit tokens into the rollup and earn fees from aggregate transaction volume, without knowing who is transacting.

**Use cases**:
- Agent-to-agent payments: Agent A pays Agent B privately. Both generate ZK proofs. Aggregator combines. Final proof settles to Stellar.
- User-to-agent payments: User deposits into rollup, agent withdraws to external wallet — no link visible on-chain.
- Micropayments: High-frequency, low-value payments batched into one aggregate proof. Marginal cost per tx → near zero.

## Success Criteria

1. Agent can generate a ZK proof of a valid state transition locally (in-browser or Node.js) in <100ms
2. Aggregator can combine N agent proofs into one aggregate proof in <10s
3. Final aggregate proof can be verified on Stellar (Soroban) in <5s
4. Individual transaction amounts, sender, and recipient are not derivable from on-chain data
5. Rollup handles ≥1000 transactions per aggregate proof
6. POC demo: two agents send private payments, aggregate proof settles to Stellar testnet

## Constraints & Assumptions

**Technical constraints**:
- Must build on Stellar/Soroban — no EVM compatibility
- Existing pool contract (`contracts/pool/`) can be modified or replaced
- No trusted setup ceremony required — prefer zkVM (RISC-V + Halo2) or PLONKish
- Recursive aggregation requires a ZK proving system that supports recursion (Halo2, Groth16 + Accumulation, or Starky)
- Stellar has no native ZK verifier — must deploy Soroban contract for proof verification

**Assumptions**:
- Agent can execute transaction logic locally (off-chain) — no need for shared contract state during execution
- State model: UTXO (notes) or account-based? UTXO pairs well with ZK. Account-based simpler but heavier ZK.
- Recursive aggregation done by a dedicated aggregator role (can be decentralized or permissioned)
- Final settlement on Stellar = tokens transferred from rollup contract to recipient address
- Bridge: Users deposit tokens to Soroban contract, tokens locked in rollup. Withdraw = tokens released from rollup.

## Questions & Open Items

| Question | Status |
|----------|--------|
| ZK backend — zkVM (RISC-V + Halo2) or custom Halo2 circuits? | **Open** — zkVM = slower proving, more flexible. Custom = faster, less general. |
| Recursive aggregation — who aggregates? Dedicated aggregator role? | **Open** — permissioned aggregator (simpler), or decentralized (PoUW-style) |
| State model — UTXO or account-based? | **Open** — UTXO better for ZK privacy (nullifier pattern). Account-based simpler integration with Soroban. |
| Bridge design — existing pool token contract, or new wrap? | **Open** — existing Stellar token (Stellar Asset) vs new Soroban token |
| How does agent execute off-chain? JS runtime? Wasmer? | **Open** — agent must run transaction logic locally to generate proof |
| Aggregator incentive — token bribe, gas fees? | **Deferred** — POC can use centralized aggregator |
| Genesis state — how does rollup initialize? | **Deferred** — POC starts with empty state |
